          <div class="review-title">marsmoon · 5.0 out of 5 stars · Great Guide for PTSD and Recovery Groups</div>
          <div class="review-meta">Reviewed in the United States on August 9, 2016 · Format: Paperback · Verified Purchase</div>
          <div class="review-body">
            <p>Practical guide to running psychoeducational groups for persons with PTSD and substance abuse. Acknowledged in the field. Provides hand outs for each meeting, discussion points, you could even read a chapter verbatim for a group meeting, and how to deal with difficult or challenging persons on a given topic. The section on grounding, methods to calm a person experiencing panic, is excellent. A great guide for counselors in training, persons who are in recovery, trauma survivors, as well as for professional counselors for ideas and directions for leading groups. Modularized format for a complete series of meetings.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="review-helpful">7 people found this helpful</div>
        </article>

        <article class="review-card">
          <div class="review-title">Bonniezinn · 5.0 out of 5 stars · the BEST resource I've found to work with clients and elicit ...</div>
          <div class="review-meta">Reviewed in the United States on April 29, 2018 · Format: Paperback · Verified Purchase</div>
          <div class="review-body">
            <p>I rarely write reviews, but felt compelled to do so in praise of this protocol. I've spent the last year working at a community mental health site for clients with substance abuse disorders. Seeking Safety is, hands down, the BEST resource I've found to work with clients and elicit change. It's intended to be used in group settings, but I've also found the materials to be useful in individual therapy. If you're working with clients with substance abuse/PTSD, you will not regret purchasing this book.</p>
          </div>
