        <article class="review-card">
          <div class="review-title">ThisGuy · 3.0 out of 5 stars · The okayest curriculum on the subject</div>
          <div class="review-meta">Reviewed in the United States on March 19, 2022 · Format: Paperback · Verified Purchase</div>
          <div class="review-body">
            <p>This is an extremely basic text that anyone with a therapeutic background and/or a long history teaching standard treatment groups will not get much from. It in fact seems to me to be geared toward the non-professional who may encounter clients with a history of trauma. I sent it back for a refund, having expected more from the large price tag and general esteem often ascribed to this text.</p>
            <p>It is also quite wordy, and covers a broad array of situations one may find themselves in while facilitating. To some this with be helpful, to others it will feel like a slog. That being said, like so many treatment group guides, some sessions seem to lack sufficient depth and do not grant much reflective capacity to the client (i.e. many of my clients would find large portions of it condescending and/or out of touch). My final cringe moment was coming across this example from a worksheet: "Working as a prostitute is making my PTSD worse; I need to stop." With all of the clients I have worked with with a substance abuse and PTSD history who were involved in sex work, I can't think of one of them that would appreciate this example or take it seriously.</p>
            <p><em>[About a year after writing this review, an institution I work with started using this curriculum as the basis for one of its groups. The facilitator, who identifies as being in addiction recovery and who has a preference for a harm reduction approach and mindfulness-based therapies, told me it reads as someone trying to understand their own journey and that it seems to come from a good place. However, he found much of the language around addiction frustrating and offensive. He said he couldn't just present the curriculum as is because it wouldn't go over well with this population (mostly veterans) and he couldn't ethically support it as is. Therefore, he uses it to process and some of the processing is about the stigmatizing language that shows up on the worksheets.]</em></p>
            <p>The organization is relatively clear even if the printing makes scanning for what you're looking for a chore. The worksheets look ancient. The beginner will still find this useful and, if still intrigued, I would highly recommend getting the used or discounted version and preparing to use this supplementally to pad existing curriculum.</p>
            <p>I want to add as an aside that each lesson begins with a quote. These quotes do not point to source material. I attempted to track a quote ostensibly made by the Buddha. It took some time to arrive at a Buddhist scholar's blog discussing this as an often misattributed quote, with some discussion about how and from where it may have emerged. Maybe nobody else cares that such a highly esteemed workbook plays fast and loose with words (including here the direct quote above), but this overall comes across as shoddy work from my perspective as a curriculum developer, an academic, and an educator.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="review-helpful">11 people found this helpful</div>
        </article>

        <article class="review-card">
          <div class="review-title">Robin H · 4.0 out of 5 stars · I'm not a professional and can follow this book.</div>
          <div class="review-meta">Reviewed in the United States on February 15, 2013 · Format: Paperback · Verified Purchase</div>
          <div class="review-body">
            <p>My husband is a soldier. A soldier that was getting punished for having PTSD and it's symptoms. I knew something was wrong about that and as I researched I realized he was not alone. The Army does not treat them together. My research led me to Seeking Safety. I was worried that I would not be able to understand it's language but for the most part I could. I have also been able to use it for my husband who is now recovering better than from any treatment the Army has tried to provide. The only thing I don't care for is the use of AA/NA being stressed. There are other recovery options available that are also successful and not based in religion or having a higher power. So obviously in those areas we just substitute the recovery program of our choice. I have now carried this book to meetings with Officers that can affect change in the system hoping that it will catch on and they will start to use it's model.</p>
          </div>
